                            Firm profile submitted by DLA Piper LLP (US)
Americas Co-Chairmen: Roger Meltzer, Jay Rains Americas 
        Co-Managing Partners: Stasia Kelly, Michael Poulos 
        Chief Operating Officer: Bob Bratt 
        Number of partners worldwide: 1,400 
        Number of lawyers worldwide: 4,300 
        Languages: Over 60 languagesInternational Offices: DLA Piper has more than 90 offices in over 40 countries. Further details can be found at www.dlapiper.com
In today’s economic environment, the concept of ‘doing business’ has become increasingly complex. More and more businesses have become global, and even local ones are affected by global forces and trends. In 2005, DLA Piper became one of the world’s largest and most prominent legal service providers through a merger of unprecedented scope. The motivation for doing so was not about size or prestige or putting pins in a map. It was to create a global organization capable of quickly and efficiently serving the most important legal needs of clients wherever they do business, whether it is across multiple jurisdictions or in a single market. Today, DLA Piper has lawyers in more than 40 countries throughout the world’s established and emerging business centers in Africa, the Americas, Asia Pacific, Europe and the Middle East. The firm’s continued international growth allows it to offer its clients the advantage of one outside law firm with the depth and geographic coverage to meet their legal needs around the world. 
        In 2015, DLA Piper combined with Davis LLP to form DLA Piper (Canada), with deep roots in the Canadian and international business communities and services across seven offices in more than 50 practices. In Latin America, the firm completed a cooperation agreement in 2016 with Bahamondez, Alvarez & Zegers in Chile, one of Chile’s leading law firms, and operates as BAZ/DLA Piper. In 2015, the firm combined with Gallastegui y Lozano in Mexico City, which brought DLA Piper together with the longstanding and distinguished reputation of GyL and its 30-year history in the Mexican legal market. The firm also began a relationship with Martinez Neira Abogados, one of Colombia’s leading law firms. DLA Piper has an ongoing cooperation agreement with Campos Mello Advogados and foreign consultancy in Brazil.
    









Corporate: 
        The firm’s lawyers support the world’s leading enterprises, emerging startup companies and financial institutions in their development and investment activities. 
        Employment: 
        The team advises clients worldwide on employment legislation helping them meet their workforce objectives. 
        Finance: 
        The firm’s lawyers provide clients with guidance and representation on all aspects of financial lending matters. Intellectual Property & Technology: The firm provides a full range of commercial, intellectual property law, privacy, sourcing, franchise and technology law services. 
        International Trade, Regulatory & Government Affairs: 
        The firm’s clients receive counsel on federal, state and local government and regulatory matters on all levels of legislation and policy. 
        Litigation, Arbitration & Investigations: 
        With skilled lawyers in litigation, arbitration, investigations and ADR, they deploy that experience to help clients devise the best strategies. 
        Projects, Energy & Infrastructure: The firm has a track record of successfully delivering first-rate legal services in all segments of the infrastructure and energy industries, and advise on energy law, infrastructure finance, transport matters and more. 
        Real Estate: 
        The firm offers a full range of services, including acquisitions and disposals, construction law, financing, land use, planning and development, leasing, environmental law, insurance and tax. Restructuring: 
        The firm’s lawyers have significant experience advising clients on investigation, enforcement, litigation and asset recovery on a multijurisdictional basis on all matters relating to public and private companies in underperforming and distressed situations. 
        Tax: The firm’s clients receive a full range of tax services that address the challenges of international commerce and business operations.
                        


